Definition 2.1.3 Let $\mathscr{A}$ be a triangulated category endowed with a non-trivial rank function. A graded algebra $\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ is called a homological unit for $\mathscr{A}$, if $\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ is maximal for the following property. For any object $\mathscr{F}\in\mathscr{A}$, there exists a pair of morphisms $i_{\mathscr{F}}:\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}\longrightarrow\mathrm{Hom% }^{\bullet}_{\mathscr{A}}(\mathscr{F},\mathscr{F})$ and $t_{\mathscr{F}}:\mathrm{Hom}^{\bullet}_{\mathscr{A}}(\mathscr{F},\mathscr{F})% \longrightarrow\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ such that: • the morphism $i_{\mathscr{F}}:\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}\longrightarrow\mathrm{Hom% }^{\bullet}_{\mathscr{A}}(\mathscr{F},\mathscr{F})$ is a graded algebra morphism which is functorial in the following sense. Let $\mathscr{F},\mathscr{G}\in\mathscr{A}$ and let $a\in\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{k}$ for some $k$. Then, for any morphism $\psi:\mathscr{F}\longrightarrow\mathscr{G}$, there is a commutative diagram: $\xymatrix{\mathscr{F}\ar[rr]^{i_{\mathscr{F}}}\ar[dd]^{\psi}&&\mathscr{F}[k]% \ar[dd]^{\psi[k]}\\ &&\\ \mathscr{G}\ar[rr]^{i_{\mathscr{G}}}&&\mathscr{G}[k]}$ • the morphism $t_{\mathscr{F}}:\mathrm{Hom}^{\bullet}_{\mathscr{A}}(\mathscr{F},\mathscr{F})% \longrightarrow\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ is a graded vector spaces morphism such that for any $\mathscr{F}\in\mathscr{A}$ and any $a\in\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$, we have $t_{\mathscr{F}}(i_{\mathscr{F}}(a))=\mathrm{rank}(\mathscr{F}).a$. With hypotheses as above, an object $\mathscr{F}\in\mathscr{A}$ is said to be unitary, if $\mathrm{Hom}^{\bullet}_{\mathscr{A}}(\mathscr{F},\mathscr{F})\simeq\mathfrak{T% }_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ as graded rings, where $\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ is a homological unit for $\mathscr{A}$.
Definition 1.0.1 Let $\mathscr{A}$ be a smooth proper triangulated category which is Calabi-Yau of dimension $3$ and endowed with a non-trivial rank function. Let $\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{\bullet}$ be a homological unit for $\mathscr{A}$ with respect to the rank function. We define the Hodge numbers of $\mathscr{A}$ as: 1. for all $i\in[0,\ldots,3]$, $h^{i,0}(\mathscr{A})=\mathfrak{T}_{\mathscr{A}}^{3-i}$, 2. $h^{3,1}(\mathscr{A})=\dim\mathrm{HH}_{-2}(\mathscr{A})-h^{2,0}(\mathscr{A})$, 3. $h^{3,2}(\mathscr{A})=h^{1,0}(\mathscr{A})$ and $h^{2,1}(\mathscr{A})=\dim\mathrm{HH}_{-1}(\mathscr{A})-h^{1,0}(\mathscr{A})-h^% {3,2}(\mathscr{A})$, 4. $h^{3,3}(\mathscr{A})=h^{0,0}(\mathscr{A})$ and $h^{1,1}(\mathscr{A})=h^{2,2}(\mathscr{A})=\dfrac{\dim\mathrm{HH}_{0}(\mathscr{% A})-h^{0,0}(\mathscr{A})-h^{3,3}(\mathscr{A})}{2}$. 5. $h^{p,q}(\mathscr{A})=h^{q,p}(\mathscr{A})$ for any $p,q\in[0,\ldots,3]$.
Definition 2.1.2 Let $\mathscr{A}$ be a smooth proper triangulated category. A rank function on $\mathscr{A}$ is a function $\mathrm{rk}:\mathscr{A}\longrightarrow\mathbb{Z}$ which is additive with respect to exact triangles and such that $\mathrm{rk}(\mathscr{F}[1])=-\mathrm{rk}(\mathscr{F})$, for any $\mathscr{F}\in\mathscr{A}$. We say that the rank function is trivial if it is the zero function and we say that it is a numerical rank function if it descends to a map: $\mathrm{rk}:\mathrm{K}_{num}(\mathscr{A})\longrightarrow\mathbb{Z},$ where $\mathrm{K}_{num}(\mathscr{A})$ is the quotient of the $\mathrm{K}$-theory of $\mathscr{A}$ by the kernel of the bilinear form: $\begin{split}\displaystyle\chi:\mathrm{K}_{0}(\mathscr{A})\times\mathrm{K}_{0}% (\mathscr{A})&\displaystyle\longrightarrow\mathbb{Z}\\ \displaystyle(\mathscr{E},\mathscr{F})&\displaystyle\longmapsto\sum_{k\geq 0}(% -1)^{k}\dim\mathrm{Ext}^{k}(\mathscr{E},\mathscr{F}).\end{split}$
Definition 2.1.1 Let $\mathscr{A}$ be a triangulated category. We say that $\mathscr{A}$ is a Calabi-Yau category of dimension $p$ if the shift by $[p]$ is a Serre functor for $\mathscr{A}$. We say furthermore that $\mathscr{A}$ is a geometric Calabi-Yau category of dimension $p$ if there exists a smooth projective variety $X$ and a semi-orthogonal decomposition $\mathrm{D^{b}}(X)=\langle\mathscr{A},{}^{\perp}{\mathscr{A}}\rangle,$ such the shift by $[p]$ is a Serre functor for $\mathscr{A}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $X$ be a Boolean space with dual algebra $B$. An $S$-valued measure (or simply a measure, if the semiring is clear from the context) on $X$ is a function $\mu\colon B\to S$ which is finitely additive, i.e. 1. $\mu(0)=0$; 2. $\mu(a\vee b)=\mu(a)+\mu(b)$ whenever $a,b\in B$ satisfy $a\wedge b=0$. Item $2$ can be expressed without reference to disjointness, in the following way: $\forall a,b\in B,\ \mu(a\vee b)+\mu(a\wedge b)=\mu(a)+\mu(b).$
Definition 5.2. The Lawson topology of a dcpo $L$ is the smallest topology containing both the Scott topology and the lower topology.
Definition 2.7. Let $T$ be any monad on $\mathbf{Set}$, and $\widehat{T}$ its profinite monad. We define $\tau\colon T\circ|-|\Rightarrow|-|\circ\widehat{T}$ to be the unique natural transformation satisfying (6). For any $X$ in $\mathbf{BStone}$, the component $\tau_{X}\colon T|X|\to|\widehat{T}X|$ is the unique function induced by the cone $\{\varphi^{*}\colon T|X|\to Y\mid(\varphi,(Y,h))\in X\downarrow G\}.$
Definition 2.3. Let $F\colon{\mathbb{C}}\to{\mathbb{D}}$ and $G\colon{\mathbb{C}}\to{\mathbb{E}}$ be any two functors. The right Kan extension of $F$ along $G$ is a pair $(K,\kappa)$, where $K\colon{\mathbb{E}}\to{\mathbb{D}}$ and $\kappa\colon K\circ G\Rightarrow F$, such that the following universal property is satisfied: for every pair $(K^{\prime},\kappa^{\prime})$ with $K^{\prime}\colon{\mathbb{E}}\to{\mathbb{D}}$ and $\kappa^{\prime}\colon K^{\prime}\circ G\Rightarrow F$, there exists a unique natural transformation $\epsilon\colon K^{\prime}\Rightarrow K$ such that the right-hand diagram below commutes. If $F=G$, the right Kan extension of $G$ along itself is called the codensity monad of $G$, and is denoted by $\mathbf{T}^{G}$. $\tikzcd{\mathbb{C}}\arrow{dd}[swap]{G}\arrow[""{name=U,below}]{rr}{F}&&{% \mathbb{D}}&&K^{\prime}\circ G\arrow[Rightarrow]{rr}{\kappa^{\prime}}\arrow[% Rightarrow]{ddr}[swap]{\epsilon G}&&F\\ &&&&&&&\\ {\mathbb{E}}\arrow[Rightarrow,to=U,shorten<=0.9em,shorten>=0.2em,"\kappa"]% \arrow{uurr}[swap,nearstart,innersep=0.1ex,""{name=V,above}]{K}\arrow[% bendright=30,xshift=10pt,yshift=-10pt]{uurr}[swap,nearstart,innersep=0.1ex,""{% name=W,above}]{K^{\prime}}\arrow[xshift=5pt,yshift=5pt,Rightarrow,from=W,to=V,% shorten<=-0.3em,shorten>=-0.1em,"\epsilon",swap,dashed]&&&&&K\circ G\arrow[% Rightarrow]{uur}[swap]{\kappa}&$
Definition 2.1. A semiring is a tuple $S=(S,+,\cdot,0,1)$ such that $(S,+,0)$ is an Abelian monoid, $(S,\cdot,1)$ is a monoid, and for all $s,t,u\in S$ the laws $\displaystyle s\cdot(t+u)=(s\cdot t)+(s\cdot u),$ $\displaystyle(t+u)\cdot s=(t\cdot s)+(u\cdot s),$ $\displaystyle s\cdot 0=0=0\cdot s$ are satisfied. A semimodule over $S$ (or $S$-semimodule, for short) is an Abelian monoid $M=(M,+_{M},0_{M})$ equipped with a ‘scalar multiplication’ of $S$, that is, a function $S\times M\to M$, $(s,m)\mapsto sm$ satisfying $\displaystyle s(m+_{M}n)=sm+_{M}sn,$ $\displaystyle(s+t)m=sm+_{M}tm,$ $\displaystyle(s\cdot t)m=s(tm),$ $\displaystyle 1m=m,$ $\displaystyle 0m=0_{M}=s0_{M}$ for all $s,t\in S$ and $m,n\in M$.
Definition 5.1. An element $k$ in a complete lattice $L$ is compact if, for every subset $S\subseteq L$ such that $k\leqslant\bigvee S$, there is a a finite subset $F\subseteq S$ with $k\leqslant\bigvee F$. An algebraic lattice is a complete lattice in which every element is the supremum of the compact elements below it.
Definition 5.4. Let $S$ be a profinite idempotent semiring. We define ${S}^{\downarrow}$ to be the topological space obtained by equipping $S$ with the dual Scott topology.
Definition 3.6. An $S$-semimodule $M$ is strongly continuous if the scalar multiplication $\alpha$ of $S$ on $M$ is not only separately continuous, but also jointly continuous. That is, $\alpha\colon S\times M\to M$ is continuous with respect to the product topology on $S\times M$.
Definition 2.8. A cosimplicial object in a category C is a functor $F\colon\Delta\to\textbf{C}$; a simplicial object in C is a functor $F\colon\Delta^{op}\to\textbf{C}.$
Definition 3.2. The DG-vector space of polynomial differential forms on the affine standard $n$-simplex is: $\Omega_{n}=\bigoplus\limits_{p=0}^{n}\Omega_{n}^{p}=\frac{\mathbb{K}[x_{0},% \dots,x_{n},dx_{0},\dots,dx_{n}]}{\left(\sum\limits_{k=0}^{n}x_{i}-1,\;\sum% \limits_{k=0}^{n}dx_{i}\right)}.$ Here $\Omega_{n}^{p}$ denotes the subspace of $p$-forms, which are the elements of degree $p$.
Definition 2.4. A morphism of contractions is a commutative diagram $\xymatrix{N\ar@(ul,ur)^{h}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{\pi}\ar[r]^{f}&B\ar@(ul,ur)^{k}\ar@<.% 5ex>[d]^{p}\\ M\ar@<.5ex>[u]^{i}\ar[r]^{\widehat{f}}&A\ar@<.5ex>[u]^{j}}$ where $f\colon N\to B$ is a morphism of DG-vector spaces such that $fh=kf.$ We denote by $\widehat{f}\colon M\to A$ the map $\widehat{f}=pfi$.
Definition 2.1. A contraction of DG-vector spaces is a diagram $\xymatrix{M\ar@<.5ex>[r]^{i}&N\ar@(ul,ur)^{h}\ar@<.5ex>[l]^{\pi}},$ with $M$ and $N$ two DG-vector spaces over $\mathbb{K}$, $h\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{K}}^{-1}(N,N)$ and $i,\;\pi$ two morphisms of DG-vector spaces. Moreover, we require the following relations: $\pi i=\text{Id}_{M},\;\quad\quad i\pi-\text{Id}_{N}=d_{N}h+hd_{N}.$
Definition 2.6. We denote with $\Delta$ the category of finite ordinals. The objects of this category are the finite ordered sets $[n]=\{0<\dots<n\}$ and its morphisms are the non decreasing maps. A special role in this category is played by face maps, which are defined as: $\delta_{k}\colon[n-1]\to[n];\quad\quad\delta_{k}(x)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{lcc% }x\quad\quad\quad\quad\text{if $p<k$}\\ x+1\quad\quad\text{ if $p\geq k$}\end{array}\right.,\quad k=0,\dots,n.$
Definition 3.1. The affine standard $n$-simplex on $\mathbb{K}$ is the set: $\Delta^{n}_{\mathbb{K}}\ =\{(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{K}^{n+1}\text{ such % that }x_{0}+\dots+x_{n}=1\}.$ The vertices of $\Delta_{\mathbb{K}}^{n}$ are the points $e_{i}\in\Delta_{\mathbb{K}}^{n}$: $e_{0}=(1,0,\dots,0),\quad e_{1}=(0,1,0,\dots,0),\quad\dots\quad,\quad e_{n}=(0% ,\dots,0,1).$
Definition 3.3 (Whitney, [17]). Fix $f\colon[m]\to[n]$ a morphism in $\Delta$. The Whitney elementary form associated to $f$ is the $m$-form: $\omega_{f}=m!\sum\limits_{i=0}^{m}(-1)^{i}x_{f(i)}dx_{f(0)}\wedge\dots\wedge% \widehat{dx_{f(i)}}\wedge\dots\wedge dx_{f(m)}\in\Omega_{n}^{m}.$ We denote with $\mathcal{C}_{n}$ the vector space spanned by Whitney elementary forms.
Definition 4.4. An interval-poset whose Hasse diagram does not contain any configuration of the form $y\to z$ and $y\to x$ where $x<y<z$ is called an exceptional interval-poset.
Definition 4.2. An interval-poset $(P,\lhd)$ is a poset over the integers $1,\cdots,n$ such that 1. If $a\lhd c$ and $a<c$, then for all integers $b$ such that $a<b<c$, we have $b\lhd c$. 2. If $c\lhd a$ and $a<c$, then for all integers $b$ such that $a<b<c$, we have $b\lhd a$.
Definition 2.5. Let $A$ be a finite dimensional $\mathbf{k}$-algebra with finite global dimension. Then $D^{b}(A)$ is $(m,n)$-fractionally Calabi-Yau if there is an isomorphism of functors $\mathbb{S}^{n}\cong[m]$.
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a tensor category and $A$ an algebra in ${\mathcal{C}}$. Then the category ${\mathcal{C}_{A}}$ has objects $(X,m_{X})$ with $X$ an object of ${\mathcal{C}}$ and $m_{X}\in\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(A\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}X,X)$ a multiplication morphism that is 1. Associative, i.e. the diagram commutes: $\begin{split}\displaystyle\xymatrix{A\boxtimes(A\boxtimes X)\ar[rr]^{\mathcal{% A}^{-1}_{A,A,X}}\ar[d]_{\text{Id}_{A}\boxtimes m_{X}}&&\displaystyle(A% \boxtimes A)\boxtimes W\ar[d]^{m\boxtimes\text{Id}_{X}}\\ \displaystyle A\boxtimes W\ar[rd]_{m_{X}}&&\displaystyle A\boxtimes W\ar[ld]^{% m_{X}}\\ &\displaystyle X&\\ \end{split}}$ 2. Unit: The composition $X\xrightarrow{\ell_{X}}\mathbf{1}\boxtimes X\xrightarrow{u\boxtimes\text{Id}_{% X}}A\boxtimes X\xrightarrow{m_{X}}X$ is the identity on $X$. Morphisms of ${\mathcal{C}_{A}}$ are all ${\mathcal{C}}$ morphisms $f\in\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ such that $\begin{split}\displaystyle\xymatrix{A\boxtimes X\ar[rr]^{\text{Id}_{A}% \boxtimes f}\ar[d]_{m_{X}}&&\displaystyle A\boxtimes Y\ar[d]^{m_{Y}}\\ \displaystyle X\ar[rr]^{f}&&\displaystyle Y\\ \end{split}}$ commutes.
Definition 2.1. [24, Def. 7.8.1] Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a braided tensor category. A algebra in ${\mathcal{C}}$ is an object $A$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ together with a multiplication map $m:A\boxtimes A\rightarrow A$ and a unit $u:\mathbf{1}\rightarrow A$ such that the multiplication is associative and compatible with left and right multiplication, i.e. the following three diagrams commute: $\begin{split}\displaystyle\xymatrix{\left(A\boxtimes A\right)\boxtimes A\ar[rr% ]^{(}0.5){\mathcal{A}_{A,A,A}}\ar[d]_{m\boxtimes\text{Id}_{A}}&&\displaystyle A% \boxtimes\left(A\boxtimes A\right)\ar[d]^{\text{Id}_{A}\boxtimes m}&\\ \displaystyle A\boxtimes A\ar[rd]_{m}&&\displaystyle A\boxtimes A\ar[ld]^{m}&% \\ &\displaystyle A&&\\ \\ \\ \displaystyle\xymatrix{\mathbf{1}\boxtimes A\ar[r]^{\ell_{A}}\ar[d]_{u% \boxtimes\text{Id}_{A}}&\displaystyle A\ar[d]^{\text{Id}_{A}}&&\displaystyle A% \boxtimes\mathbf{1}\ar[r]^{r_{A}}\ar[d]_{\text{Id}_{A}\boxtimes u}&% \displaystyle A\ar[d]^{\text{Id}_{A}}\\ \displaystyle A\boxtimes A\ar[r]^{m}&\displaystyle A&&\displaystyle A\boxtimes A% \ar[r]^{m}&\displaystyle A\\ \end{split}}}$ The algebra $A$ is called haploid if the dimension of $\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(\mathbf{1},A)$ is one. $A$ is commutative if the diagram $\xymatrix{A\boxtimes A\ar[rd]_{m}\ar[rr]^{c_{A,A}}&&A\boxtimes A\ar[ld]^{m}&\\ &A&&\\ }$ commutes.
Definition 2.3. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a braided tensor category and $A$ a commutative algebra in ${\mathcal{C}}$. Then the category ${\mathcal{C}_{A}^{\text{loc}}}\subset{\mathcal{C}_{A}}$ of local modules is the full tensor subcategory whose objects are local with respect to $A$, i.e. $\begin{split}\displaystyle\xymatrix{A\boxtimes X\ar[rd]_{m_{X}}\ar[rr]^{M_{A,X% }}&&\displaystyle A\boxtimes X\ar[ld]^{m_{X}}\\ &\displaystyle X&\\ \end{split}}$ commutes.
Definition 5.1 (Magnitude cohomology of enriched categories). Let $X$ be a $\mathcal{V}$-category The magnitude cochain complex $C_{\Sigma}^{\ast}(X)$ of $X$ is the cochain complex in $\mathcal{A}$ obtained by setting $C_{\Sigma}^{k}(X)=[C_{k}^{\Sigma}(X),1_{\mathcal{A}}],$ with the induced differential $\partial^{\ast}=[\partial,1_{\mathcal{A}}]$. The normalized magnitude cochain complex $N_{\Sigma}^{\ast}(X)$ of $X$ is defined by $N_{\Sigma}^{k}(X)=[N_{k}^{\Sigma}(X),1_{\mathcal{A}}]$ with $\partial^{\ast}=[\partial,1_{\mathcal{A}}]$. The magnitude cohomology $H_{\Sigma}^{\ast}(X)$ is defined to be the cohomology of the magnitude cochains, or equivalently of the normalized magnitude cochains: $H_{\Sigma}^{\ast}(X)=H^{\ast}(C_{\Sigma}^{\ast}(X))\cong H^{\ast}(N_{\Sigma}^{% \ast}(X)).$
Definition 7.2 (Codes and admissible simplices). • Given a vertex $x$ of $C_{n}$ and $i\in\{-m,\ldots,0,\ldots,m\}$, we let $x+i$ denote the vertex obtained by moving $|i|$ places from $x$, clockwise if $i>0$, and anticlockwise if $i<0$. • Given a simplex ${\underline{x}}=(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})$, we obtain a sequence $\underline{i}=(i_{1},\ldots,i_{k})$ with entries in $\{-m,\ldots,-1,1,\ldots,m\}$ defined by $x_{j}=x_{j-1}+i_{j}$. We call $\underline{i}$ the code of ${\underline{x}}$. Note that the code of a $0$-simplex $(x_{0})$ is the empty tuple $()$. • A code is called admissible if, after dividing it into the maximal subsequences whose entries all have the same sign, the subsequences all have one of the following forms for some $j\geqslant 0$. $\underbrace{(1,m,1,m,\ldots)}_{j\text{ entries}}\qquad\underbrace{(-1,-m,1,-m% \ldots)}_{j\text{ entries}}$ Note that while these sequences begin with $\pm 1$, they can end with $\pm 1$ or $\pm m$, according to whether $j$ is odd or even. • A simplex is admissible if its code is admissible.
Definition 7.9 (Monomials from admissible tuples). Suppose given an admissible simplex ${\underline{x}}$ with code $()$, $(1)$, $(-1)$, $(1,m)$ or $(-1,-m)$. Then we define $p_{\underline{x}}\in\mathrm{MH}^{\ast}_{\ast}(C_{n})$ to be the class $e_{x_{0}}$, $a_{x_{0}x_{1}}$ or $b_{x_{0}x_{2}}$ dual to $[{\underline{x}}]$. More generally, if ${\underline{x}}=(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})$ is an admissible simplex with $k>0$, then there is a unique way to decompose ${\underline{x}}$ into ‘pieces’ ${\underline{x}}_{1}=(x_{i_{0}},\ldots,x_{i_{1}}),\ {\underline{x}}_{2}=(x_{i_{% 1}},\ldots,x_{i_{2}}),\ \ldots,\ {\underline{x}}_{r}=(x_{i_{r-1}},\ldots,x_{i_% {r}}),$ with $i_{0}=0$ and $i_{r}=k$, such that each piece has code $(1)$, $(-1)$, $(1,m)$ or $(-1,-m)$, and in this case we define $p_{\underline{x}}=p_{{\underline{x}}_{1}}\cdots p_{{\underline{x}}_{r}}$.
Definition 2.2 (Magnitude cohomology). Let $X$ be a generalised metric space. The magnitude cochain complex of $X$ is the dual to the magnitude chain complex: $\mathrm{MC}_{\ell}^{\ast}(X)=\operatorname{Hom}(\mathrm{MC}_{\ast,\ell}(X),% \mathbb{Z}).$ The magnitude cohomology of $X$, denoted $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast}^{\ast}(X)$, is the cohomology of the magnitude cochains: $\mathrm{MH}_{\ell}^{\ast}(X)=H^{\ast}(\mathrm{MC}_{\ell}^{\ast}(X)).$ If $f\colon X\to Y$ is a non-increasing map of generalised metric spaces, then the dual of $f_{\#}$ gives the induced cochain map $f^{\#}\colon\mathrm{MC}_{\ast}^{\ast}(X)\longrightarrow\mathrm{MC}_{\ast}^{% \ast}(Y)$ and the induced map in cohomology $f^{\ast}\colon\mathrm{MH}_{\ast}^{\ast}(X)\longrightarrow\mathrm{MH}_{\ast}^{% \ast}(Y).$ Given $\varphi\in\mathrm{MC}^{k_{1}}_{\ell_{1}}(X)$ and $\psi\in\mathrm{MC}^{k_{2}}_{\ell_{2}}(X)$, the product $\varphi\cdot\psi\in\mathrm{MC}^{k_{1}+k_{2}}_{\ell_{1}+\ell_{2}}(X)$ is defined by $(\varphi\cdot\psi)(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k_{1}+k_{2}})=\varphi(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k_{1}% })\cdot\psi(x_{k_{1}},\ldots,x_{k_{1}+k_{2}})$ for any $(k_{1}+k_{2})$-simplex $(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k_{1}+k_{2}})$. The unit $u\in\mathrm{MC}^{0}_{0}(X)$ is the cochain defined by the rule $u(x_{0})=1$ for every $0$-simplex $(x_{0})$. The reader may readily verify that the product is strictly associative and unital, with unit $u$, and that it satisfies the Leibniz rule $\partial^{\ast}(\varphi\cdot\psi)=\partial^{\ast}\varphi\cdot\psi+(-1)^{k_{1}}% \varphi\cdot\partial^{\ast}\psi.$ Consequently, there is an induced product on magnitude cohomology $\mathrm{MH}_{\ell_{1}}^{k_{1}}(X)\otimes\mathrm{MH}_{\ell_{2}}^{k_{2}}(X)% \longrightarrow\mathrm{MH}_{\ell_{1}+\ell_{2}}^{k_{1}+k_{2}}(X),\quad\alpha% \otimes\beta\longmapsto\alpha\cdot\beta$ that makes $\mathrm{MH}^{\ast}_{\ast}(X)$ into a unital, associated bigraded ring with unit $1=[u]\in\mathrm{MH}^{0}_{0}(X)$. We refer to $\mathrm{MH}^{\ast}_{\ast}(X)$, equipped with the product, as the magnitude cohomology ring. The assignment $X\mapsto\mathrm{MH}^{\ast}_{\ast}(X)$, $f\mapsto f^{\ast}$ is a contravariant functor from the category of metric spaces and non-increasing maps into the category of unital associative bigraded rings.
Definition 5.3 (The magnitude cohomology ring). The maps $\Delta$ and $\varepsilon$ induce dual maps $\mu\colon C^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)\otimes C^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)\longrightarrow C^{% \ast}_{\Sigma}(X),\qquad\eta\colon 1_{\mathrm{Ch}_{\mathcal{A}}}% \longrightarrow C^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)$ defined by $\mu=[\Delta,1_{\mathcal{A}}]$ and $\eta=[\varepsilon,1_{\mathcal{A}}]$ making $C^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)$ into an associative, unital dg-algebra in the abelian category $\mathcal{A}$. They induce maps of the same name in homology $\mu\colon H^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)\otimes H^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)\longrightarrow H^{% \ast}_{\Sigma}(X),\qquad\eta\colon 1_{\mathcal{A}}\longrightarrow H^{\ast}_{% \Sigma}(X)$ and these make $H^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)$ into an associative unital graded algebra in $\mathcal{A}$. The same definitions can be carried out using the normalized chains, and produce the same strucutre on $H^{\ast}_{\Sigma}(X)$.
Definition 2.1 (Magnitude homology). We recall the definition of magnitude homology from sections 2 and 3 of [HW17] (for graphs) and section 7 of [LS17] (for arbitrary metric spaces). Let $X$ be a generalised metric space. A $k$-simplex or just simplex in $X$ is a tuple $(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})$ of elements of $X$ in which consecutive entries are distinct, i.e. $x_{0}\neq x_{1}\neq\cdots\neq x_{k}$. The degree of the simplex $(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})$ is $k$, and its length is $\ell(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})=d(x_{0},x_{1})+\cdots+d(x_{k-1},x_{k}).$ The magnitude chain complex of $X$, denoted $\mathrm{MC}_{\ast,\ast}(X)$, is the chain complex of $\mathbb{R}$-graded abelian groups defined as follows. The $k$-chains in degree $\ell$, denoted $\mathrm{MC}_{k,\ell}(X)$, is defined to be the free abelian group on the simplices of degree $k$ and length $\ell$: $\mathrm{MC}_{k,\ell}(X)=\mathbb{Z}\left\{(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})\in X^{k+1}\mid% \ell(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})=\ell,\ x_{0}\neq x_{1}\neq\cdots\neq x_{k}\right\}$ The differential $\partial\colon\mathrm{MC}_{k,l}(X)\longrightarrow\mathrm{MC}_{k-1,l}(X)$ is defined by $\partial=-\partial_{1}+\partial_{2}-\cdots+(-1)^{k-1}\partial_{k-1}$ where $\partial_{i}(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}(x_{0},\ldots,% \widehat{x_{i}},\ldots,x_{k})&\text{if }d(x_{i-1},x_{i+1})=d(x_{i-1},x_{i})+d(% x_{i},x_{i+1}),\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{array}\right.$ The magnitude homology $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast,\ast}(X)$ of $X$ is the homology of the magnitude chain complex: $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast,\ell}(X)=H_{\ast}(\mathrm{MC}_{\ast,\ell}(X)).$ Note that in [LS17] $\mathrm{MH}_{k,\ell}(X)$ is denoted by $H^{\Sigma,\ell}_{k}(X)$. If $f\colon X\to Y$ is a map of generalised metric spaces that does not increase distances, i.e. $d_{Y}(f(x),f(x^{\prime}))\leqslant d_{X}(x,x^{\prime})$ for all $x,x^{\prime}\in X$, then the induced chain map $f_{\#}\colon\mathrm{MC}_{\ast,\ast}(X)\to\mathrm{MC}_{\ast,\ast}(Y)$ is defined by $f_{\#}(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}(f(x_{0}),\ldots,f(x_{k})% )&\text{if }\ell(f(x_{0}),\ldots,f(x_{k}))=\ell(x_{0},\ldots,x_{k})\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{array}\right.$ The induced map in homology is the map $f_{\ast}\colon\mathrm{MH}_{\ast,\ast}(X)\longrightarrow\mathrm{MH}_{\ast,\ast}% (Y)$ obtained from $f_{\#}$.
Definition 6.1 (Path algebra of a graph). Let $G$ be a graph. An edge path in $G$ is a sequence $x_{0}\cdots x_{k}$ of vertices of $G$ such that each pair $x_{i-1},x_{i}$ span an edge. Sequences of length $k=0$ are allowed. The path algebra of $G$ is the $\mathbb{Z}$-algebra with basis the edge paths in $G$, and multiplication is given by concatenation, where possible: $(x_{0}\cdots x_{k})\cdot(y_{0}\cdots y_{l})=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}x_{0}% \cdots x_{k}y_{1}\cdots y_{l}&\text{if }x_{k}=y_{0}\\ 0&\text{otherwise}\end{array}\right.$ Thus the path algebra of $G$ is the path algebra of the quiver obtained from $G$ by doubling each edge to give two oriented edges, one in each direction. (See [Cra92, section 1] for the definition of quivers and their path algebras. We have defined our path algebras over $\mathbb{Z}$, but it seems that path algebras of quivers are usually defined as $k$-algebras for a field $k$.) We make the path algebra into a graded algebra using path-length.
Definition 4.1 (Magnitude homology). Given a $\mathcal{V}$-category $X$, the magnitude nerve of $X$ is the simplicial object $B^{\Sigma}_{\bullet}(X)$ in $\mathcal{A}$ defined by $B^{\Sigma}_{k}(X)=\bigoplus_{x_{0},\ldots,x_{k}}\Sigma X(x_{0},x_{1})\otimes% \cdots\otimes\Sigma X(x_{k-1},x_{k})$ where the sum is over all tuples $x_{0},\ldots,x_{k}$ of objects of $X$. The inner face maps $d_{1},\ldots,d_{k-1}$ are defined using monoidality of $\Sigma$ and composition in $X$, and have the effect of replacing two adjacent factors $\Sigma X(x_{i-1},x_{i})\otimes\Sigma X(x_{i},x_{i+1})$ with a single factor $\Sigma X(x_{i-1},x_{i+1})$. The outer face maps $d_{0}$ and $d_{k}$ are defined using terminality of $1_{\mathcal{V}}$ and monoidality of $\Sigma$, and have the effect of erasing the first and last factors $\Sigma X(x_{0},x_{1})$ and $\Sigma X(x_{k-1},x_{k})$ respectively. The degeneracy maps $s_{i}$ are defined using the identity maps of $X$ and monoidality of $\Sigma$, and have the effect of inserting a factor $\Sigma X(x_{i},x_{i})$ between $\Sigma X(x_{i-1},x_{i})$ and $\Sigma X(x_{i},x_{i+1})$. We leave it to the reader to write out the simplicial structure maps in detail for themselves, or to unpack them from sections 3 and 4 of [LS17] if they wish. Note that Leinster and Shulman write $B^{\Sigma}_{\bullet}(X)$ as $B_{\bullet}(\Sigma X,\mathbbm{1})$. The magnitude chain complex $C^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)$ of $X$ is defined to be the chain complex $C_{\ast}(B^{\Sigma}_{\bullet}(X))$ of $B^{\Sigma}_{\bullet}(X)$. Thus $C^{\Sigma}_{k}(X)=\bigoplus_{x_{0},\ldots,x_{k}}\Sigma X(x_{0},x_{1})\otimes% \cdots\otimes\Sigma X(x_{k-1},x_{k})$ and $\partial\colon C_{k}^{\Sigma}(X)\longrightarrow C_{k-1}^{\Sigma}(X)$ is defined by $\partial=d_{0}-d_{1}+\cdots+(-1)^{k}d_{k}$. The normalized magnitude chain complex $N_{\ast}^{k}(X)$ of $X$ is the normalised chain complex $N_{\ast}(B_{\bullet}^{\Sigma}(X))$ of $B_{\bullet}^{\Sigma}(X)$. This is the quotient of $C_{\ast}(B_{\bullet}^{\Sigma}(X))$ by the subcomplex generated by the images of the degeneracy maps. We refer the reader to sections 8.2 and 8.3 of [Wei94]. The magnitude homology $H^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)$ of $X$ is the homology of the magnitude chains of $X$, or equivalently the homology of the normalised magnitude chains of $X$: $H^{\Sigma}_{k}(X)=H_{k}(C^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X))\cong H_{k}(N_{\ast}^{\Sigma}(X)).$
Definition 7.7. The universal coefficient sequence of Remark 2.5 gives an isomorphism of $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast}^{\ast}(C_{n})$ with the dual of $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast,\ast}(C_{n})$, and so we obtain the basis of $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast}^{\ast}(C_{n})$ dual to the one of Theorem 7.5. Using this dual basis we define elements of $\mathrm{MH}_{\ast}^{\ast}(C_{n})$ as follows. • For each vertex $x$, $e_{x}\in\mathrm{MH}_{0}^{0}(C_{n})$ is the dual to $[(x)]\in\mathrm{MH}_{0,0}(C_{n})$. • For each oriented edge $(x,y)$, $a_{xy}\in\mathrm{MH}^{1}_{1}(C_{n})$ is the dual to $[(x,y)]\in\mathrm{MH}_{1,1}(C_{n})$. • For each pair $x,z$ with $d(x,z)=m$, $b_{xz}\in\mathrm{MH}^{2}_{m+1}(C_{n})$ denotes the dual to $[(x,y,z)]\in\mathrm{MH}_{2,m+1}(C_{n})$. Here $y$ is determined by the conditions $d(x,y)=1$, $d(y,z)=m$ as in Example 7.6.
Definition 5.2 (The coproduct and counit). Let $X$ be a $\mathcal{V}$-category. We define the coproduct $\Delta\colon C^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)\longrightarrow C^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)\otimes C% ^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)$ to be the sum of the maps $\Delta\colon C^{\Sigma}_{p+q}(X)\to C^{\Sigma}_{p}(X)\otimes C^{\Sigma}_{q}(x)$ that send the $x_{0},\ldots,x_{p+q}$ summand into the product of the $x_{0},\ldots,x_{p}$ and $x_{p},\ldots,x_{p+q}$ summands by the evident map from $\Sigma X(x_{0},x_{1})\otimes\cdots\otimes\Sigma X(x_{p+q-1},x_{p+q})$ to $\left(\Sigma X(x_{0},x_{1})\otimes\cdots\otimes\Sigma X(x_{p-1},x_{p})\right)% \otimes\left(\Sigma X(x_{p},x_{p+1})\otimes\cdots\otimes\Sigma X(x_{p+q-1},x_{% p+q})\right).$ It is a chain map. We further define the counit map $\varepsilon\colon C^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)\longrightarrow 1_{\mathrm{Ch}_{\mathcal% {A}}}$ to be the map that is given by $0$ in positive degrees and in degree $0$ by the map $C_{0}^{\Sigma}(X)\to 1_{\mathrm{Ch}\mathcal{A}}$, $\bigoplus_{x_{0}}1_{\mathcal{A}}\to 1_{\mathcal{A}}$ that is the identity on each summand. Again, this is a chain map. Furthermore, the coproduct and counit both reduce to maps on the normalized magnitude chains, that we also call the coproduct and counit $\Delta\colon N^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)\longrightarrow N^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)\otimes N% ^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X),\qquad\varepsilon\colon N^{\Sigma}_{\ast}(X)\to 1_{\mathrm% {Ch}_{\mathcal{A}}}.$ These maps make $C_{\ast}^{\Sigma}(X)$ and $N_{\ast}^{\Sigma}(X)$ into coassociative, counital differential graded coalgebras in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 2.1. An $n$-dimensional affine manifold is a real manifold equipped with a specified atlas consisting of charts $\psi_{i}:U_{i}\xrightarrow{\sim}V_{i}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$ such that all of the composites $\psi_{i}\circ\psi_{j}^{-1}\colon V_{ji}\rightarrow V_{ij}$ are affine maps between the subsets $V_{ji}=\psi_{j}(U_{i}\cap U_{j})$ and $V_{ij}=\psi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j})$ of $\mathbb{R}^{n}$. Here a map $f:V\rightarrow W$ between subsets $V\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$ and $W\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{m}$ is said to be affine if it has constant Jacobian, or equivalently, if it is the restriction of a map $F:\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{m}$ that is affine in the usual sense, i.e. a composite of a linear map followed by a translation.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a category. A tangent structure on $\mathbb{C}$ consists of the following structure: • A functor $T\colon\mathbb{C}\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$ (thought of as the tangent functor); • A projection, i.e. a natural transformation $p\colon T\rightarrow id_{\mathbb{C}}$; • Fibre powers of $p$, i.e for each object $M$ of $\mathbb{C}$ and each natural number $n$ there is a fibre product4Recall that a fibre product of a family of morphisms with common codomain $M$ in $\mathbb{C}$ is a product in the slice category $\mathbb{C}/M$. Each fibre product in $\mathbb{C}$ determines an associated diagram in $\mathbb{C}$, called a fibre product diagram, consisting of the base object $M$, the given family of morphisms, and the product projections for the fibre product. Just as with pullbacks, fibre products are equivalently described as certain limits in $\mathbb{C}$. of $n$ copies of $p_{M}$, written as $T_{n}M\rightarrow M$, and this fibre product is preserved by each iterate $T^{m}$ of $T$; • Additive bundle structure, i.e natural transformations $+\colon T_{2}\rightarrow T$ and $0\colon id\rightarrow T$ making each projection $p_{M}$ an additive bundle, i.e., a commutative monoid in the slice category over $M$ in $\mathbb{C}$; • A vertical lift natural transformation $\ell:T\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0% pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}% }\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont% \char